          "body": "After commissioning the people and Joshua, Moses turns to institutional infrastructure. He completes the writing of the Torah and hands it to the Levitical priests who carry the ark (31:9). He then commands a seven-year public reading cycle at the Feast of Booths — the full text, before all Israel, including women, children, and resident aliens (31:10-12). The breadth of the audience is striking: this is not esoteric knowledge for specialists but the covenant document of the whole people. The purpose is triple: that they may hear, learn, and fear the LORD, and be careful to observe (31:12). And crucially, the children who do not yet know are included — each reading cycle is a generation-forming event (31:13). The Torah beside the ark (31:26) serves a different function: it is the fixed legal text that functions as a witness against unfaithfulness, inaccessible to casual tampering, deposited in the holiest institutional space available."
